{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019tCfbfecQJzxD6fvGyPC1V","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Specification: [301] Async Event Queue\n     2→\n     3→## Meta\n     4→\n     5→| Field | Value |\n     6→|-------|-------|\n     7→| Status | Ready |\n     8→| Priority | P1 |\n     9→| Track | Core |\n    10→| NR_OF_TRIES | 0 |\n    11→\n    12→---\n    13→\n    14→## Overview\n    15→\n    16→A Postgres-backed async event queue that decouples the critical game settlement path from secondary side-effects: reward delivery, claim payouts, achievement evaluation, notifications, and analytics. The queue is a platform-level primitive — not tied to any single feature — with the referral system (spec 300) as its first consumer.\n    17→\n    18→**Why this exists:** The settlement worker is the hot path. Every millisecond of latency there is felt by players waiting for results. Side-effects like sending SOL, granting rewards, checking achievements, or firing notifications are slower, can fail independently, and must never block or degrade the game loop. A queue also provides natural backpressure — 50 games settling simultaneously don't DDoS the treasury wallet or external services.\n    19→\n    20→## User Stories\n    21→\n    22→- As a platform developer, I want to emit events from the settlement path without adding latency so that players see results instantly\n    23→- As a platform developer, I want failed side-effects to retry automatically so that transient failures (RPC timeouts, treasury wallet congestion) self-heal\n    24→- As an operator, I want visibility into dead events so that I can investigate and manually resolve stuck operations\n    25→- As a platform developer, I want to register new event handlers without modifying the queue infrastructure so that new features plug in cleanly\n    26→\n    27→---\n    28→\n    29→## Capability Alignment\n    30→\n    31→- **`docs/SCOPE.md` references**: Section 7 \"Non-Functional Baseline\" → Reliability, Observability\n    32→- **Current baseline fit**: Not Implemented\n    33→- **Planning bucket**: Core (infrastructure primitive)\n    34→\n    35→## Required Context Files\n    36→\n    37→- Backend settlement worker (current hot path)\n    38→- Backend DB client and migration system (see `docs/solutions/` or memory for patterns)\n    39→- `docs/FOUNDATIONS.md` — architecture patterns\n    40→\n    41→## Contract Files\n    42→\n    43→- No existing mocks — new infrastructure\n    44→- Producer API and worker interface defined in FR-2 and FR-3 below\n    45→\n    46→---\n    47→\n    48→## Functional Requirements\n    49→\n    50→### FR-1: Event Table Schema\n    51→\n    52→A single `event_queue` table in the existing Postgres database. No external dependencies — no Redis, no RabbitMQ, no SQS.\n    53→\n    54→```sql\n    55→CREATE TABLE event_queue (\n    56→  id              BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n    57→  event_type      TEXT NOT NULL,\n    58→  payload         JSONB NOT NULL,\n    59→  status          TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT 'pending',\n    60→  attempts        INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,\n    61→  max_attempts    INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 3,\n    62→  scheduled_at    TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),\n    63→  started_at      TIMESTAMPTZ,\n    64→  completed_at    TIMESTAMPTZ,\n    65→  error           TEXT,\n    66→  created_at      TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()\n    67→);\n    68→\n    69→-- Partial index for worker polling — only scans pending events\n    70→CREATE INDEX idx_event_queue_poll\n    71→  ON event_queue (scheduled_at)\n    72→  WHERE status = 'pending';\n    73→\n    74→-- Index for observability queries (dead events, recent failures)\n    75→CREATE INDEX idx_event_queue_status ON event_queue (status, created_at);\n    76→```\n    77→\n    78→**Status lifecycle:**\n    79→```\n    80→pending → processing → completed\n    81→                    → failed → pending (retry with backoff)\n    82→                             → dead (max_attempts exceeded)\n    83→```\n    84→\n    85→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    86→- [ ] `event_queue` table created via migration\n    87→- [ ] Partial index on `(scheduled_at) WHERE status = 'pending'` exists\n    88→- [ ] Status index for observability queries exists\n    89→- [ ] Status values constrained to: `pending`, `processing`, `completed`, `failed`, `dead`\n    90→\n    91→### FR-2: Event Producer API\n    92→\n    93→A minimal function that inserts an event into the queue. Designed to be called **within an existing DB transaction** so the event is committed atomically with the triggering operation.\n    94→\n    95→```typescript\n    96→// Signature\n    97→async function emitEvent(\n    98→  tx: DatabaseTransaction,   // existing transaction handle\n    99→  eventType: string,\n   100→  payload: Record<string, unknown>,\n   101→  options?: {\n   102→    maxAttempts?: number;     // default: 3\n   103→    scheduledAt?: Date;       // default: now (for delayed events)\n   104→  }\n   105→): Promise<{ eventId: bigint }>;\n   106→```\n   107→\n   108→**Usage example (in settlement worker):**\n   109→```typescript\n   110→await db.transaction(async (tx) => {\n   111→  // 1. Existing: write settlement outcome\n   112→  await settleGame(tx, roundId, outcome);\n   113→\n   114→  // 2. Existing: insert referral earnings (fast, inline)\n   115→  await insertReferralEarning(tx, referrerWallet, ...);\n   116→\n   117→  // 3. New: emit event for async processing (reward delivery, notifications)\n   118→  await emitEvent(tx, 'referral.game_settled', {\n   119→    referrerWallet, refereeWallet, roundId, gameType, wagerLamports, earnedLamports\n   120→  });\n   121→});\n   122→// All three committed atomically — or none.\n   123→```\n   124→\n   125→**Key property:** If the settlement transaction rolls back, the event is never created. No orphan events. No missed events.\n   126→\n   127→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   128→- [ ] `emitEvent()` function inserts into `event_queue` within the provided transaction\n   129→- [ ] Event is committed atomically with the triggering operation\n   130→- [ ] Default `max_attempts` is 3, overridable per event\n   131→- [ ] `scheduled_at` defaults to `now()`, supports future scheduling for delayed events\n   132→- [ ] Returns the created event's ID\n   133→\n   134→### FR-3: Event Worker\n   135→\n   136→A single polling loop that runs inside the existing backend process. No separate service, no separate deploy.\n   137→\n   138→**Polling loop:**\n   139→1. Every 1-2 seconds, query for ready events:\n   140→   ```sql\n   141→   UPDATE event_queue\n   142→   SET status = 'processing', started_at = now()\n   143→   WHERE id IN (\n   144→     SELECT id FROM event_queue\n   145→     WHERE status = 'pending' AND scheduled_at <= now()\n   146→     ORDER BY scheduled_at\n   147→     LIMIT 10\n   148→     FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED\n   149→   )\n   150→   RETURNING *;\n   151→   ```\n   152→2. For each claimed event, look up the handler by `event_type` and call it\n   153→3. On handler success → `status = 'completed'`, `completed_at = now()`\n   154→4. On handler failure:\n   155→   - Increment `attempts`\n   156→   - If `attempts < max_attempts` → `status = 'pending'`, `scheduled_at = now() + backoff(attempts)`\n   157→   - If `attempts >= max_attempts` → `status = 'dead'`, `error = error_message`\n   158→5. Log all state transitions for observability\n   159→\n   160→**Backoff schedule (exponential):**\n   161→- Attempt 1 failure → retry after 5 seconds\n   162→- Attempt 2 failure → retry after 30 seconds\n   163→- Attempt 3 failure → dead (manual review)\n   164→\n   165→Backoff is configurable per event type if needed, but defaults are fine for v1.\n   166→\n   167→**`SKIP LOCKED` is critical:** If the worker is slow or a handler takes a while, the next poll skips events already being processed. This prevents double-processing and enables future multi-worker scaling without code changes.\n   168→\n   169→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   170→- [ ] Worker loop starts automatically with the backend process\n   171→- [ ] Polls every 1-2 seconds (configurable via env)\n   172→- [ ] Claims batch of up to 10 events using `FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED`\n   173→- [ ] Successfully processed events transition to `completed`\n   174→- [ ] Failed events retry with exponential backoff (5s, 30s, then dead)\n   175→- [ ] Dead events have error message recorded\n   176→- [ ] All state transitions are logged (event_id, type, old_status → new_status)\n   177→- [ ] Worker gracefully stops on process shutdown (finishes current batch, then exits)\n   178→\n   179→### FR-4: Handler Registry\n   180→\n   181→A simple map from event type strings to handler functions. New features register handlers at startup — no queue code changes needed.\n   182→\n   183→```typescript\n   184→type EventHandler = (payload: Record<string, unknown>) => Promise<void>;\n   185→\n   186→const handlers = new Map<string, EventHandler>();\n   187→\n   188→function registerHandler(eventType: string, handler: EventHandler): void;\n   189→function getHandler(eventType: string): EventHandler | undefined;\n   190→```\n   191→\n   192→**Rules:**\n   193→- One handler per event type (not a pub/sub fan-out — keep it simple for v1)\n   194→- If no handler is registered for an event type, the event is marked `dead` immediately with error \"no handler registered\"\n   195→- Handlers must be idempotent — re-processing a completed event should be a safe no-op\n   196→\n   197→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   198→- [ ] Handlers can be registered by event type string\n   199→- [ ] Worker looks up handler for each event's `event_type`\n   200→- [ ] Unhandled event types are marked `dead` with descriptive error\n   201→- [ ] Handler interface is a simple `async (payload) => void` function\n   202→- [ ] Handlers are registered at backend startup before worker begins polling\n   203→\n   204→### FR-5: Idempotency\n   205→\n   206→Events may be processed more than once (crash during processing, worker restart). Handlers MUST be idempotent.\n   207→\n   208→**Pattern:** Before performing the side-effect, check if it was already done. For example:\n   209→- Claim handler: check if `referral_claims` already has a row for this event's claim_id\n   210→- Reward handler: check if reward was already granted for this round_id + referee pair\n   211→- Notification handler: check if notification was already sent\n   212→\n   213→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   214→- [ ] Each handler checks for prior completion before executing the side-effect\n   215→- [ ] Re-processing a `completed` event is a safe no-op (no duplicate SOL transfers, no duplicate rewards)\n   216→- [ ] Idempotency checks use the event payload (round_id, wallet, etc.), not the event_queue.id\n   217→\n   218→### FR-6: Observability\n   219→\n   220→Operators need to know when events are failing and when the queue is backed up.\n   221→\n   222→**Minimum observability (v1):**\n   223→- Log every state transition at INFO level: `[EventQueue] event=12345 type=referral.game_settled pending→processing`\n   224→- Log handler errors at ERROR level with full error + payload\n   225→- Dead events logged at WARN level with a clear \"MANUAL REVIEW NEEDED\" prefix\n   226→- Basic health stats available via internal endpoint or startup log: queue depth (pending count), dead count, processing count\n   227→\n   228→**Future (v2):**\n   229→- Metrics export (Prometheus/Grafana)\n   230→- Dead event alerting (Slack/PagerDuty)\n   231→- Admin UI for retrying dead events\n   232→\n   233→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   234→- [ ] All state transitions logged at INFO level\n   235→- [ ] Handler errors logged at ERROR level with payload context\n   236→- [ ] Dead events logged at WARN level with \"MANUAL REVIEW\" prefix\n   237→- [ ] Queue depth (pending count) queryable for health checks\n   238→\n   239→---\n   240→\n   241→**Note:** Referral event types and handlers (originally FR-7) have been moved to spec 300 (Referral System). Spec 301 delivers the queue infrastructure only. Spec 300 registers its handlers using the `registerHandler()` API provided here.\n   242→\n   243→---\n   244→\n   245→## Design Decisions\n   246→\n   247→### Why Postgres and not Redis/BullMQ/SQS\n   248→\n   249→| Consideration | Postgres Queue | External Queue |\n   250→|---|---|---|\n   251→| New infrastructure | None — already have Postgres | Redis/SQS to deploy + maintain |\n   252→| Transactional atomicity | Event insert in same `BEGIN...COMMIT` as settlement | Two-phase: settle, then enqueue (can lose events on crash) |\n   253→| Durability | WAL-backed, survives restarts | Redis: depends on persistence config. SQS: durable. |\n   254→| Concurrent workers | `SKIP LOCKED` — proper lock-free concurrency | Native in most queue systems |\n   255→| Throughput | Dozens/sec is trivial, hundreds/sec is fine | Designed for thousands+/sec |\n   256→| Operational complexity | Zero — one fewer thing to monitor | Another service to keep alive |\n   257→\n   258→**Verdict:** At current throughput (dozens of games/minute), Postgres is the right choice. The migration path to an external queue is clean — swap the `emitEvent()` implementation, the handler interface stays identical.\n   259→\n   260→### Why not a pub/sub fan-out\n   261→\n   262→One handler per event type (not multiple subscribers). This is simpler, easier to reason about, and sufficient for v1. If we need fan-out later (e.g., `game.settled` triggers both referral + achievement + analytics handlers), we can either:\n   263→- Emit multiple event types from the producer (explicit, traceable)\n   264→- Add a fan-out layer in the handler registry (one event → multiple handlers)\n   265→\n   266→The explicit multi-emit approach is preferred because each downstream concern can have independent retry semantics.\n   267→\n   268→---\n   269→\n   270→## Success Criteria\n   271→\n   272→- Events emitted during settlement add < 2ms latency to the hot path\n   273→- Failed handlers retry and self-heal without manual intervention (up to max_attempts)\n   274→- Dead events are visible and actionable via logs\n   275→- New event types can be added by registering a handler — no queue infrastructure changes\n   276→- No event loss — events committed atomically with their triggering operation\n   277→- No double-processing — `SKIP LOCKED` + idempotent handlers guarantee exactly-once semantics in practice\n   278→\n   279→---\n   280→\n   281→## Dependencies\n   282→\n   283→- Existing Postgres database and migration system\n   284→- Backend process lifecycle (worker starts/stops with the server)\n   285→\n   286→## Assumptions\n   287→\n   288→- Postgres version supports `SKIP LOCKED` (9.5+ — already met)\n   289→- Current throughput stays under hundreds of events/second (well within Postgres queue performance)\n   290→- Single backend process for v1 (multi-worker scaling is supported by design but not required)\n   291→\n   292→---\n   293→\n   294→## Validation Plan\n   295→\n   296→| # | Acceptance Criterion | Validation Method | Evidence Required |\n   297→|---|---------------------|-------------------|-------------------|\n   298→| 1 | Event table + indexes created | Migration test: run migration, inspect schema | DB schema dump |\n   299→| 2 | `emitEvent()` is transactional | Integration test: emit in tx, rollback, verify event doesn't exist | Test output |\n   300→| 3 | Worker polls and processes events | Integration test: emit event, verify handler called within poll interval | Test output |\n   301→| 4 | `SKIP LOCKED` prevents double-processing | Test: two concurrent poll calls, verify each event processed exactly once | Test output |\n   302→| 5 | Failed events retry with backoff | Integration test: handler throws, verify attempts increment + scheduled_at delayed | Test output + DB check |\n   303→| 6 | Dead events flagged after max_attempts | Integration test: handler always fails, verify status = 'dead' after 3 attempts | Test output + DB check |\n   304→| 7 | Unhandled event types marked dead | Integration test: emit event with no handler, verify dead + error message | Test output |\n   305→| 8 | Graceful shutdown | Integration test: signal shutdown mid-batch, verify current events complete | Test output |\n   306→| 9 | Observability logging | Integration test: process events, verify INFO/ERROR/WARN logs at correct levels | Log output |\n   307→| 10 | Worker wired into backend startup | Backend starts, worker loop begins polling | Startup log |\n   308→\n   309→---\n   310→\n   311→## Completion Signal\n   312→\n   313→### Implementation Checklist\n   314→\n   315→<!-- Refined 2026-03-21. Each item = one autonomous iteration.\n   316→     Codebase context:\n   317→     - Backend: services/backend/, Hono + postgres npm package, custom JSON logger\n   318→     - Migrations: services/backend/migrations/ (numbered SQL files, next = 010)\n   319→     - DB transactions: sql.begin(async (tx) => { ... })\n   320→     - Worker pattern: setTimeout(loop, interval) with isRunning flag (see settlement.ts)\n   321→     - Startup: src/index.ts initializes workers + starts HTTP server\n   322→     - Logger: src/logger.ts — logger.info/warn/error(message, fields)\n   323→     - FR-7 (referral handlers) moved to spec 300. This spec delivers queue infra only.\n   324→-->\n   325→\n   326→- [ ] [backend] Create `services/backend/migrations/010_event_queue.sql` with the `event_queue` table (schema from FR-1), partial index `idx_event_queue_poll` on `(scheduled_at) WHERE status = 'pending'`, status+created_at index `idx_event_queue_status`, and CHECK constraint on status values (`pending`, `processing`, `completed`, `failed`, `dead`). Verify with `pnpm migrate`. (FR-1)\n   327→\n   328→- [ ] [backend] Create `services/backend/src/queue/event-types.ts`: export an `EventTypes` const object with all known event type strings (initially: `REFERRAL_CODE_APPLIED`, `REFERRAL_GAME_SETTLED`, `REFERRAL_CLAIM_REQUESTED`) and a `EventType` union type derived via `typeof EventTypes[keyof typeof EventTypes]`. Create `services/backend/src/queue/handler-registry.ts`: export `registerHandler(eventType: EventType, handler)`, `getHandler(eventType: string)`, and the `EventHandler` type (`(payload: Record<string, unknown>) => Promise<void>`). Backed by a `Map<string, EventHandler>`. Create `services/backend/src/queue/emit-event.ts`: export `emitEvent(tx, eventType: EventType, payload, options?)` that inserts into `event_queue` using the provided `postgres` transaction handle. Default `max_attempts = 3`, `scheduled_at = now()`. Return `{ eventId }`. Using `EventType` in both `emitEvent` and `registerHandler` makes typos a compile error instead of a dead event at runtime. (FR-2, FR-4)\n   329→\n   330→- [ ] [backend] Create `services/backend/src/queue/worker.ts`: export `createEventWorker(sql, options?)` returning `{ start(), stop() }`. The worker polls every `options.pollIntervalMs` (default 1500ms) using `setTimeout(loop, interval)` pattern. Each poll: claim up to 10 events with `UPDATE ... WHERE id IN (SELECT ... FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED) RETURNING *`, dispatch each to handler via `getHandler(event.event_type)`, on success set `status = 'completed', completed_at = now()`. If no handler registered for event type → mark `dead` with error `\"no handler registered for: {type}\"`. Log state transitions at INFO via `logger.info`. (FR-3, FR-4, FR-6)\n   331→\n   332→- [ ] [backend] Add failure handling to the worker in `worker.ts`: on handler error, increment `attempts`. If `attempts < max_attempts` → set `status = 'pending'`, `scheduled_at = now() + backoff` (attempt 1: 5s, attempt 2: 30s, attempt 3+: 5min). If `attempts >= max_attempts` → set `status = 'dead'`, record `error = error.message`. Log handler errors at ERROR level with payload context. Log dead events at WARN level with `\"MANUAL REVIEW NEEDED\"` prefix. (FR-3, FR-6)\n   333→\n   334→- [ ] [backend] Add graceful shutdown to the worker: `stop()` sets an `isShuttingDown` flag — current poll batch finishes but no new polls are scheduled. Create `services/backend/src/queue/health.ts`: export `getQueueDepth(sql)` returning `{ pending, processing, dead, completed }` counts. Create `services/backend/src/queue/index.ts` barrel file re-exporting `emitEvent`, `registerHandler`, `getHandler`, `createEventWorker`, `getQueueDepth`, and the `EventHandler` type. (FR-3, FR-6)\n   335→\n   336→- [ ] [backend] Wire the event worker into backend startup in `services/backend/src/index.ts`: import `createEventWorker` from `./queue`, create the worker with the DB connection, call `worker.start()` alongside existing settlement worker and PDA watcher initialization. Add optional `EVENT_QUEUE_POLL_MS` to config parsing in `src/config.ts` (default 1500). Log `\"Event queue worker started\"` at INFO level on startup. (FR-3)\n   337→\n   338→- [ ] [test] Add unit tests in `services/backend/src/queue/__tests__/queue.test.ts` (vitest): (1) `emitEvent` inserts a row with correct fields and returns eventId; (2) `emitEvent` within a rolled-back `sql.begin()` does NOT persist the event; (3) handler registry: register → get returns it, get for unknown type returns undefined; (4) backoff calculation: attempt 1 → +5s, attempt 2 → +30s, attempt 3 → dead. Tests require a real Postgres database — use `DATABASE_URL` env var (same as backend). (FR-1, FR-2, FR-3, FR-4)\n   339→\n   340→- [ ] [test] Add integration tests in `services/backend/src/queue/__tests__/queue-integration.test.ts` (vitest): (1) Happy path: register a mock handler that resolves, emit event via `emitEvent`, start worker, assert handler was called and event status = `completed` within 3s; (2) Failure → retry → dead: register handler that always throws, emit event, verify attempts increment with backoff delays, verify final status = `dead` with error message recorded; (3) Concurrent safety: emit 5 events, start two worker instances polling same table, verify each event processed exactly once (handler call count = 5, not 10). (FR-3, FR-5)\n   341→\n   342→- [ ] [test] N/A — no local E2E coverage (backend-only infrastructure, no web flows). N/A — no visual coverage (no UI). N/A — no devnet E2E (no external provider integration).\n   343→\n   344→### Testing Requirements\n   345→\n   346→The agent MUST complete ALL before outputting the completion signal:\n   347→\n   348→#### Code Quality\n   349→- [ ] All existing tests pass (`pnpm test` from monorepo root)\n   350→- [ ] New queue unit + integration tests pass\n   351→- [ ] No lint errors (`pnpm lint`)\n   352→\n   353→#### Functional Verification\n   354→- [ ] All FR-1 through FR-6 acceptance criteria verified via tests\n   355→- [ ] Edge cases: empty poll (no pending events), unhandled event type, max_attempts exceeded\n   356→- [ ] Error states: handler throws sync/async error, zero events to poll\n   357→\n   358→#### Visual Regression\n   359→- [ ] N/A — no UI component in this spec\n   360→\n   361→#### Smoke Test (Human-in-the-Loop)\n   362→\n   363→- [ ] Start backend, verify \"Event queue worker started\" appears in startup logs\n   364→- [ ] Manually INSERT a test event into `event_queue`, verify worker picks it up within 2-3s\n   365→- [ ] Insert event with no handler registered, verify it goes to `dead` with error logged\n   366→- [ ] Stop backend (Ctrl+C), restart, verify no stuck `processing` events\n   367→\n   368→### Iteration Instructions\n   369→\n   370→If ANY check fails:\n   371→1. Identify the specific issue\n   372→2. Fix the code\n   373→3. Re-run tests\n   374→4. Re-verify all criteria\n   375→5. Check again\n   376→\n   377→**Only when ALL checks pass, output:** `<promise>DONE</promise>`\n   378→\n   379→### Post-Completion: Gap Analysis\n   380→\n   381→After the spec loop outputs `<promise>DONE</promise>`, `spec-loop.sh` automatically runs\n   382→`/gap-analysis {id} --non-interactive` which:\n   383→1. Audits every FR acceptance criterion against the codebase\n   384→2. Writes `docs/specs/{id}/gap-analysis.md` with inventory + audit + recommendations\n   385→3. Annotates FR checkboxes with HTML comment evidence (`<!-- satisfied: ... -->`)\n   386→4. Commits everything together with the completion commit\n   387→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"04709d28-c77b-4687-bdb5-b2ffc1a1c744","uuid":"71528441-069e-4486-a5b2-7b772e586eda","timestamp":"2026-03-21T13:02:23.763Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspaces/rng-utopia/docs/specs/301-async-event-queue/spec.md","content":"# Specification: [301] Async Event Queue\n\n## Meta\n\n| Field | Value |\n|-------|-------|\n| Status | Ready |\n| Priority | P1 |\n| Track | Core |\n| NR_OF_TRIES | 0 |\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nA Postgres-backed async event queue that decouples the critical game settlement path from secondary side-effects: reward delivery, claim payouts, achievement evaluation, notifications, and analytics. The queue is a platform-level primitive — not tied to any single feature — with the referral system (spec 300) as its first consumer.\n\n**Why this exists:** The settlement worker is the hot path. Every millisecond of latency there is felt by players waiting for results. Side-effects like sending SOL, granting rewards, checking achievements, or firing notifications are slower, can fail independently, and must never block or degrade the game loop. A queue also provides natural backpressure — 50 games settling simultaneously don't DDoS the treasury wallet or external services.\n\n## User Stories\n\n- As a platform developer, I want to emit events from the settlement path without adding latency so that players see results instantly\n- As a platform developer, I want failed side-effects to retry automatically so that transient failures (RPC timeouts, treasury wallet congestion) self-heal\n- As an operator, I want visibility into dead events so that I can investigate and manually resolve stuck operations\n- As a platform developer, I want to register new event handlers without modifying the queue infrastructure so that new features plug in cleanly\n\n---\n\n## Capability Alignment\n\n- **`docs/SCOPE.md` references**: Section 7 \"Non-Functional Baseline\" → Reliability, Observability\n- **Current baseline fit**: Not Implemented\n- **Planning bucket**: Core (infrastructure primitive)\n\n## Required Context Files\n\n- Backend settlement worker (current hot path)\n- Backend DB client and migration system (see `docs/solutions/` or memory for patterns)\n- `docs/FOUNDATIONS.md` — architecture patterns\n\n## Contract Files\n\n- No existing mocks — new infrastructure\n- Producer API and worker interface defined in FR-2 and FR-3 below\n\n---\n\n## Functional Requirements\n\n### FR-1: Event Table Schema\n\nA single `event_queue` table in the existing Postgres database. No external dependencies — no Redis, no RabbitMQ, no SQS.\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE event_queue (\n  id              BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n  event_type      TEXT NOT NULL,\n  payload         JSONB NOT NULL,\n  status          TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT 'pending',\n  attempts        INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,\n  max_attempts    INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 3,\n  scheduled_at    TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),\n  started_at      TIMESTAMPTZ,\n  completed_at    TIMESTAMPTZ,\n  error           TEXT,\n  created_at      TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()\n);\n\n-- Partial index for worker polling — only scans pending events\nCREATE INDEX idx_event_queue_poll\n  ON event_queue (scheduled_at)\n  WHERE status = 'pending';\n\n-- Index for observability queries (dead events, recent failures)\nCREATE INDEX idx_event_queue_status ON event_queue (status, created_at);\n```\n\n**Status lifecycle:**\n```\npending → processing → completed\n                    → failed → pending (retry with backoff)\n                             → dead (max_attempts exceeded)\n```\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] `event_queue` table created via migration\n- [ ] Partial index on `(scheduled_at) WHERE status = 'pending'` exists\n- [ ] Status index for observability queries exists\n- [ ] Status values constrained to: `pending`, `processing`, `completed`, `failed`, `dead`\n\n### FR-2: Event Producer API\n\nA minimal function that inserts an event into the queue. Designed to be called **within an existing DB transaction** so the event is committed atomically with the triggering operation.\n\n```typescript\n// Signature\nasync function emitEvent(\n  tx: DatabaseTransaction,   // existing transaction handle\n  eventType: string,\n  payload: Record<string, unknown>,\n  options?: {\n    maxAttempts?: number;     // default: 3\n    scheduledAt?: Date;       // default: now (for delayed events)\n  }\n): Promise<{ eventId: bigint }>;\n```\n\n**Usage example (in settlement worker):**\n```typescript\nawait db.transaction(async (tx) => {\n  // 1. Existing: write settlement outcome\n  await settleGame(tx, roundId, outcome);\n\n  // 2. Existing: insert referral earnings (fast, inline)\n  await insertReferralEarning(tx, referrerWallet, ...);\n\n  // 3. New: emit event for async processing (reward delivery, notifications)\n  await emitEvent(tx, 'referral.game_settled', {\n    referrerWallet, refereeWallet, roundId, gameType, wagerLamports, earnedLamports\n  });\n});\n// All three committed atomically — or none.\n```\n\n**Key property:** If the settlement transaction rolls back, the event is never created. No orphan events. No missed events.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] `emitEvent()` function inserts into `event_queue` within the provided transaction\n- [ ] Event is committed atomically with the triggering operation\n- [ ] Default `max_attempts` is 3, overridable per event\n- [ ] `scheduled_at` defaults to `now()`, supports future scheduling for delayed events\n- [ ] Returns the created event's ID\n\n### FR-3: Event Worker\n\nA single polling loop that runs inside the existing backend process. No separate service, no separate deploy.\n\n**Polling loop:**\n1. Every 1-2 seconds, query for ready events:\n   ```sql\n   UPDATE event_queue\n   SET status = 'processing', started_at = now()\n   WHERE id IN (\n     SELECT id FROM event_queue\n     WHERE status = 'pending' AND scheduled_at <= now()\n     ORDER BY scheduled_at\n     LIMIT 10\n     FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED\n   )\n   RETURNING *;\n   ```\n2. For each claimed event, look up the handler by `event_type` and call it\n3. On handler success → `status = 'completed'`, `completed_at = now()`\n4. On handler failure:\n   - Increment `attempts`\n   - If `attempts < max_attempts` → `status = 'pending'`, `scheduled_at = now() + backoff(attempts)`\n   - If `attempts >= max_attempts` → `status = 'dead'`, `error = error_message`\n5. Log all state transitions for observability\n\n**Backoff schedule (exponential):**\n- Attempt 1 failure → retry after 5 seconds\n- Attempt 2 failure → retry after 30 seconds\n- Attempt 3 failure → dead (manual review)\n\nBackoff is configurable per event type if needed, but defaults are fine for v1.\n\n**`SKIP LOCKED` is critical:** If the worker is slow or a handler takes a while, the next poll skips events already being processed. This prevents double-processing and enables future multi-worker scaling without code changes.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] Worker loop starts automatically with the backend process\n- [ ] Polls every 1-2 seconds (configurable via env)\n- [ ] Claims batch of up to 10 events using `FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED`\n- [ ] Successfully processed events transition to `completed`\n- [ ] Failed events retry with exponential backoff (5s, 30s, then dead)\n- [ ] Dead events have error message recorded\n- [ ] All state transitions are logged (event_id, type, old_status → new_status)\n- [ ] Worker gracefully stops on process shutdown (finishes current batch, then exits)\n\n### FR-4: Handler Registry\n\nA simple map from event type strings to handler functions. New features register handlers at startup — no queue code changes needed.\n\n```typescript\ntype EventHandler = (payload: Record<string, unknown>) => Promise<void>;\n\nconst handlers = new Map<string, EventHandler>();\n\nfunction registerHandler(eventType: string, handler: EventHandler): void;\nfunction getHandler(eventType: string): EventHandler | undefined;\n```\n\n**Rules:**\n- One handler per event type (not a pub/sub fan-out — keep it simple for v1)\n- If no handler is registered for an event type, the event is marked `dead` immediately with error \"no handler registered\"\n- Handlers must be idempotent — re-processing a completed event should be a safe no-op\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] Handlers can be registered by event type string\n- [ ] Worker looks up handler for each event's `event_type`\n- [ ] Unhandled event types are marked `dead` with descriptive error\n- [ ] Handler interface is a simple `async (payload) => void` function\n- [ ] Handlers are registered at backend startup before worker begins polling\n\n### FR-5: Idempotency\n\nEvents may be processed more than once (crash during processing, worker restart). Handlers MUST be idempotent.\n\n**Pattern:** Before performing the side-effect, check if it was already done. For example:\n- Claim handler: check if `referral_claims` already has a row for this event's claim_id\n- Reward handler: check if reward was already granted for this round_id + referee pair\n- Notification handler: check if notification was already sent\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] Each handler checks for prior completion before executing the side-effect\n- [ ] Re-processing a `completed` event is a safe no-op (no duplicate SOL transfers, no duplicate rewards)\n- [ ] Idempotency checks use the event payload (round_id, wallet, etc.), not the event_queue.id\n\n### FR-6: Observability\n\nOperators need to know when events are failing and when the queue is backed up.\n\n**Minimum observability (v1):**\n- Log every state transition at INFO level: `[EventQueue] event=12345 type=referral.game_settled pending→processing`\n- Log handler errors at ERROR level with full error + payload\n- Dead events logged at WARN level with a clear \"MANUAL REVIEW NEEDED\" prefix\n- Basic health stats available via internal endpoint or startup log: queue depth (pending count), dead count, processing count\n\n**Future (v2):**\n- Metrics export (Prometheus/Grafana)\n- Dead event alerting (Slack/PagerDuty)\n- Admin UI for retrying dead events\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] All state transitions logged at INFO level\n- [ ] Handler errors logged at ERROR level with payload context\n- [ ] Dead events logged at WARN level with \"MANUAL REVIEW\" prefix\n- [ ] Queue depth (pending count) queryable for health checks\n\n---\n\n**Note:** Referral event types and handlers (originally FR-7) have been moved to spec 300 (Referral System). Spec 301 delivers the queue infrastructure only. Spec 300 registers its handlers using the `registerHandler()` API provided here.\n\n---\n\n## Design Decisions\n\n### Why Postgres and not Redis/BullMQ/SQS\n\n| Consideration | Postgres Queue | External Queue |\n|---|---|---|\n| New infrastructure | None — already have Postgres | Redis/SQS to deploy + maintain |\n| Transactional atomicity | Event insert in same `BEGIN...COMMIT` as settlement | Two-phase: settle, then enqueue (can lose events on crash) |\n| Durability | WAL-backed, survives restarts | Redis: depends on persistence config. SQS: durable. |\n| Concurrent workers | `SKIP LOCKED` — proper lock-free concurrency | Native in most queue systems |\n| Throughput | Dozens/sec is trivial, hundreds/sec is fine | Designed for thousands+/sec |\n| Operational complexity | Zero — one fewer thing to monitor | Another service to keep alive |\n\n**Verdict:** At current throughput (dozens of games/minute), Postgres is the right choice. The migration path to an external queue is clean — swap the `emitEvent()` implementation, the handler interface stays identical.\n\n### Why not a pub/sub fan-out\n\nOne handler per event type (not multiple subscribers). This is simpler, easier to reason about, and sufficient for v1. If we need fan-out later (e.g., `game.settled` triggers both referral + achievement + analytics handlers), we can either:\n- Emit multiple event types from the producer (explicit, traceable)\n- Add a fan-out layer in the handler registry (one event → multiple handlers)\n\nThe explicit multi-emit approach is preferred because each downstream concern can have independent retry semantics.\n\n---\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- Events emitted during settlement add < 2ms latency to the hot path\n- Failed handlers retry and self-heal without manual intervention (up to max_attempts)\n- Dead events are visible and actionable via logs\n- New event types can be added by registering a handler — no queue infrastructure changes\n- No event loss — events committed atomically with their triggering operation\n- No double-processing — `SKIP LOCKED` + idempotent handlers guarantee exactly-once semantics in practice\n\n---\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- Existing Postgres database and migration system\n- Backend process lifecycle (worker starts/stops with the server)\n\n## Assumptions\n\n- Postgres version supports `SKIP LOCKED` (9.5+ — already met)\n- Current throughput stays under hundreds of events/second (well within Postgres queue performance)\n- Single backend process for v1 (multi-worker scaling is supported by design but not required)\n\n---\n\n## Validation Plan\n\n| # | Acceptance Criterion | Validation Method | Evidence Required |\n|---|---------------------|-------------------|-------------------|\n| 1 | Event table + indexes created | Migration test: run migration, inspect schema | DB schema dump |\n| 2 | `emitEvent()` is transactional | Integration test: emit in tx, rollback, verify event doesn't exist | Test output |\n| 3 | Worker polls and processes events | Integration test: emit event, verify handler called within poll interval | Test output |\n| 4 | `SKIP LOCKED` prevents double-processing | Test: two concurrent poll calls, verify each event processed exactly once | Test output |\n| 5 | Failed events retry with backoff | Integration test: handler throws, verify attempts increment + scheduled_at delayed | Test output + DB check |\n| 6 | Dead events flagged after max_attempts | Integration test: handler always fails, verify status = 'dead' after 3 attempts | Test output + DB check |\n| 7 | Unhandled event types marked dead | Integration test: emit event with no handler, verify dead + error message | Test output |\n| 8 | Graceful shutdown | Integration test: signal shutdown mid-batch, verify current events complete | Test output |\n| 9 | Observability logging | Integration test: process events, verify INFO/ERROR/WARN logs at correct levels | Log output |\n| 10 | Worker wired into backend startup | Backend starts, worker loop begins polling | Startup log |\n\n---\n\n## Completion Signal\n\n### Implementation Checklist\n\n<!-- Refined 2026-03-21. Each item = one autonomous iteration.\n     Codebase context:\n     - Backend: services/backend/, Hono + postgres npm package, custom JSON logger\n     - Migrations: services/backend/migrations/ (numbered SQL files, next = 010)\n     - DB transactions: sql.begin(async (tx) => { ... })\n     - Worker pattern: setTimeout(loop, interval) with isRunning flag (see settlement.ts)\n     - Startup: src/index.ts initializes workers + starts HTTP server\n     - Logger: src/logger.ts — logger.info/warn/error(message, fields)\n     - FR-7 (referral handlers) moved to spec 300. This spec delivers queue infra only.\n-->\n\n- [ ] [backend] Create `services/backend/migrations/010_event_queue.sql` with the `event_queue` table (schema from FR-1), partial index `idx_event_queue_poll` on `(scheduled_at) WHERE status = 'pending'`, status+created_at index `idx_event_queue_status`, and CHECK constraint on status values (`pending`, `processing`, `completed`, `failed`, `dead`). Verify with `pnpm migrate`. (FR-1)\n\n- [ ] [backend] Create `services/backend/src/queue/event-types.ts`: export an `EventTypes` const object with all known event type strings (initially: `REFERRAL_CODE_APPLIED`, `REFERRAL_GAME_SETTLED`, `REFERRAL_CLAIM_REQUESTED`) and a `EventType` union type derived via `typeof EventTypes[keyof typeof EventTypes]`. Create `services/backend/src/queue/handler-registry.ts`: export `registerHandler(eventType: EventType, handler)`, `getHandler(eventType: string)`, and the `EventHandler` type (`(payload: Record<string, unknown>) => Promise<void>`). Backed by a `Map<string, EventHandler>`. Create `services/backend/src/queue/emit-event.ts`: export `emitEvent(tx, eventType: EventType, payload, options?)` that inserts into `event_queue` using the provided `postgres` transaction handle. Default `max_attempts = 3`, `scheduled_at = now()`. Return `{ eventId }`. Using `EventType` in both `emitEvent` and `registerHandler` makes typos a compile error instead of a dead event at runtime. (FR-2, FR-4)\n\n- [ ] [backend] Create `services/backend/src/queue/worker.ts`: export `createEventWorker(sql, options?)` returning `{ start(), stop() }`. The worker polls every `options.pollIntervalMs` (default 1500ms) using `setTimeout(loop, interval)` pattern. Each poll: claim up to 10 events with `UPDATE ... WHERE id IN (SELECT ... FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED) RETURNING *`, dispatch each to handler via `getHandler(event.event_type)`, on success set `status = 'completed', completed_at = now()`. If no handler registered for event type → mark `dead` with error `\"no handler registered for: {type}\"`. Log state transitions at INFO via `logger.info`. (FR-3, FR-4, FR-6)\n\n- [ ] [backend] Add failure handling to the worker in `worker.ts`: on handler error, increment `attempts`. If `attempts < max_attempts` → set `status = 'pending'`, `scheduled_at = now() + backoff` (attempt 1: 5s, attempt 2: 30s, attempt 3+: 5min). If `attempts >= max_attempts` → set `status = 'dead'`, record `error = error.message`. Log handler errors at ERROR level with payload context. Log dead events at WARN level with `\"MANUAL REVIEW NEEDED\"` prefix. (FR-3, FR-6)\n\n- [ ] [backend] Add graceful shutdown to the worker: `stop()` sets an `isShuttingDown` flag — current poll batch finishes but no new polls are scheduled. Create `services/backend/src/queue/health.ts`: export `getQueueDepth(sql)` returning `{ pending, processing, dead, completed }` counts. Create `services/backend/src/queue/index.ts` barrel file re-exporting `emitEvent`, `registerHandler`, `getHandler`, `createEventWorker`, `getQueueDepth`, and the `EventHandler` type. (FR-3, FR-6)\n\n- [ ] [backend] Wire the event worker into backend startup in `services/backend/src/index.ts`: import `createEventWorker` from `./queue`, create the worker with the DB connection, call `worker.start()` alongside existing settlement worker and PDA watcher initialization. Add optional `EVENT_QUEUE_POLL_MS` to config parsing in `src/config.ts` (default 1500). Log `\"Event queue worker started\"` at INFO level on startup. (FR-3)\n\n- [ ] [test] Add unit tests in `services/backend/src/queue/__tests__/queue.test.ts` (vitest): (1) `emitEvent` inserts a row with correct fields and returns eventId; (2) `emitEvent` within a rolled-back `sql.begin()` does NOT persist the event; (3) handler registry: register → get returns it, get for unknown type returns undefined; (4) backoff calculation: attempt 1 → +5s, attempt 2 → +30s, attempt 3 → dead. Tests require a real Postgres database — use `DATABASE_URL` env var (same as backend). (FR-1, FR-2, FR-3, FR-4)\n\n- [ ] [test] Add integration tests in `services/backend/src/queue/__tests__/queue-integration.test.ts` (vitest): (1) Happy path: register a mock handler that resolves, emit event via `emitEvent`, start worker, assert handler was called and event status = `completed` within 3s; (2) Failure → retry → dead: register handler that always throws, emit event, verify attempts increment with backoff delays, verify final status = `dead` with error message recorded; (3) Concurrent safety: emit 5 events, start two worker instances polling same table, verify each event processed exactly once (handler call count = 5, not 10). (FR-3, FR-5)\n\n- [ ] [test] N/A — no local E2E coverage (backend-only infrastructure, no web flows). N/A — no visual coverage (no UI). N/A — no devnet E2E (no external provider integration).\n\n### Testing Requirements\n\nThe agent MUST complete ALL before outputting the completion signal:\n\n#### Code Quality\n- [ ] All existing tests pass (`pnpm test` from monorepo root)\n- [ ] New queue unit + integration tests pass\n- [ ] No lint errors (`pnpm lint`)\n\n#### Functional Verification\n- [ ] All FR-1 through FR-6 acceptance criteria verified via tests\n- [ ] Edge cases: empty poll (no pending events), unhandled event type, max_attempts exceeded\n- [ ] Error states: handler throws sync/async error, zero events to poll\n\n#### Visual Regression\n- [ ] N/A — no UI component in this spec\n\n#### Smoke Test (Human-in-the-Loop)\n\n- [ ] Start backend, verify \"Event queue worker started\" appears in startup logs\n- [ ] Manually INSERT a test event into `event_queue`, verify worker picks it up within 2-3s\n- [ ] Insert event with no handler registered, verify it goes to `dead` with error logged\n- [ ] Stop backend (Ctrl+C), restart, verify no stuck `processing` events\n\n### Iteration Instructions\n\nIf ANY check fails:\n1. Identify the specific issue\n2. Fix the code\n3. Re-run tests\n4. Re-verify all criteria\n5. Check again\n\n**Only when ALL checks pass, output:** `<promise>DONE</promise>`\n\n### Post-Completion: Gap Analysis\n\nAfter the spec loop outputs `<promise>DONE</promise>`, `spec-loop.sh` automatically runs\n`/gap-analysis {id} --non-interactive` which:\n1. Audits every FR acceptance criterion against the codebase\n2. Writes `docs/specs/{id}/gap-analysis.md` with inventory + audit + recommendations\n3. Annotates FR checkboxes with HTML comment evidence (`<!-- satisfied: ... -->`)\n4. Commits everything together with the completion commit\n","numLines":387,"startLine":1,"totalLines":387}}}
